            <fr:title text="Tensor Products">Tensor Products</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>Suppose we want to consider a <fr:link href="/forest/0004/" title="How to Make a Map" uri="https://andrewczezowski.github.io/forest/0004/" display-uri="0004" type="local">map</fr:link>, which takes the <fr:link href="/forest/0001/" title="Cartesian Product" uri="https://andrewczezowski.github.io/forest/0001/" display-uri="0001" type="local">cartesian product</fr:link> of a <fr:link href="/forest/0003/" title="Elementary Vector Space" uri="https://andrewczezowski.github.io/forest/0003/" display-uri="0003" type="local">vector space</fr:link> with itself to the real numbers.</html:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\_\_:V\times  V\rightarrow \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>
            <html:p>We do not want to create anything new for our map, so the obvious choice is to draw the map from the dual space.</html:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\set {v,w,...}\in  V\; and\; \set {\alpha ,\beta ,...}\in  V^*]]></fr:tex>
            <html:p>We define the tensor product, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta \otimes \alpha ]]></fr:tex>, which linearly maps an ordered pair of numbers to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex></html:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\left [\beta \otimes \alpha \right ] (v,w)=\braket {\beta ,v}\braket {\alpha ,w}]]></fr:tex>
            <html:p>and using its linearity,</html:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[[a\beta \otimes \alpha +b\gamma \otimes \delta ] (v,w)=a[\beta \otimes \alpha ] (v,w)+b[\gamma \otimes \delta ] (v,w)]]></fr:tex>
            <html:p>If we consider the set of all possible tensor products of covectors: we have a linear space, with the notion of addition, and scalar multiplication; which satisfies all of the <fr:link href="/forest/0003/" title="Elementary Vector Space" uri="https://andrewczezowski.github.io/forest/0003/" display-uri="0003" type="local">properties of a vector space</fr:link>. So, all tensor product spaces are vector spaces; and since the elements of a vector space are vectors, all tensors are vectors. Such a space is also called a Tensor Product Space.</html:p>
            <html:p>An arbitrary tensor can be written as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta \otimes \gamma \equiv  T_{\mu \nu }e^\mu \otimes  e^\nu ]]></fr:tex></html:p>
            <html:p>This idea can be easily generalized to consider higher order and mixed tensors. For instance,</html:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[V^*\otimes  V^*\otimes  V^*:V\times  V\times  V \rightarrow  \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>4</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>9</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://andrewczezowski.github.io/forest/0009/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>0009</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/forest/0009/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Rank of a Tensor Product Space">Rank of a Tensor Product Space</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>What we call tensors are objects where vectors are first and dual vectors are second. This does not mean that objects that do not follow this ordering are illogical, but we do not assign them a rank as a tensor.</html:p>
                <html:p>The idea of a rank:
<html:ul><html:li>A vector: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A^\mu  e_\mu \rightarrow ]]></fr:tex> rank (1,0)</html:li>
  <html:li>A covector: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A_\mu  e^\mu \rightarrow ]]></fr:tex>rank (0,1)</html:li>
  <html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[T^{\mu \nu \delta \lambda }e_\mu \otimes  e_\nu \otimes  e_\delta \otimes  e_\lambda \rightarrow ]]></fr:tex> rank (4,0)</html:li>
  <html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[T_{\mu \nu \delta \lambda }\;e^\mu \otimes  e^\nu \otimes  e^\delta \otimes  e^\lambda \rightarrow ]]></fr:tex>rank (0,4)</html:li>
  <html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[T^{\mu \nu }{}_{\delta \lambda }\;e_\mu \otimes  e_\nu \otimes  e^\delta \otimes  e^\lambda \rightarrow ]]></fr:tex>rank (2,2)</html:li>
  <html:li>...</html:li></html:ul></html:p>
                <html:p>We use the notation,</html:p>
                <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[V\otimes  V^*\otimes  V^*\equiv \mathcal {T}^1{}_2=\set {All\; possible\; tensors\; of\; rank\; (1,2)}]]></fr:tex>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
